PYTHON VIRTUAL ENVIRONMENT
A Python virtual environment (venv) is an isolated Python workspace that keeps a project's dependencies
separate from other projects and from your system Python.

Think of it like this:
Your Computer
│
├── Project A
│   ├── Django 4.2
│   └── requests 2.31
│
├── Project B
│   ├── Flask 3.0
│   └── requests 2.28
│
└── System Python

Without virtual environments, all packages get installed globally and projects can conflict with each other.


Production practice (pip freeze requirements.txt)
Use:
pip freeze > requirements.txt
Then later:
pip install -r requirements.txt
This is the standard workflow used in most Python projects.

What about pip list > requirements.txt?
You can do:
pip list > requirements.txt (It creates a human readable file (Package_name   Package_version))
but the file will look like:
Package                Version
---------------------  -------
chromadb               1.0.15
sentence-transformers  5.0.0
This is not a valid requirements file.
If you try:
pip install -r requirements.txt
it will fail because pip expects:
package==version